HARD LINK and SOFT LINK

✅ Hard Link
A hard link is another name (entry) for the same physical file in the filesystem. It directly points to the same inode, 
meaning both the original file and the hard link share the exact same data. If one file is deleted, the data is still 
accessible through the other link because the inode remains until all links are removed. Hard links cannot be created 
across different filesystems and are generally not allowed for directories.

Key Points:

Points to the same inode (same file data)
Data survives even if the original file is deleted
Cannot cross filesystems
Cannot link directories (except special cases)
No difference between original file and hard link


✅ Soft Link (Symbolic Link)
A soft link (symbolic link) is a special file that acts as a pointer to the path of another file. It does not store 
actual data but references the original file location. If the original file is deleted or moved, the soft link becomes 
broken because it depends on the file path. Soft links are flexible as they can span across filesystems and can also link directories.
Key Points:

Points to file path (acts like shortcut)
Breaks if original file is deleted or moved
Can cross filesystems
Can link directories
Has its own inode (different from original file)

